    <sem:object xml:lang="eng" datatype="xsd:string">In the New Testament, Peter was originally known as Simeon or Simon (), a fisherman of Bethsaida living at Capernaum with his wife. Jesus healed Peter’s wife’s mother (). Peter was called with his brother Andrew to be a disciple of Jesus Christ (; ; ). His Aramaic name, Cephas, meaning “a seer” or “stone,” was given to him by the Lord (; ). While the New Testament mentions some of Peter’s mortal weaknesses, it also illustrates that he overcame them and was made strong by his faith in Jesus Christ.The first epistle was written from “Babylon” (probably Rome) and was sent to the Saints in what is now called Asia Minor soon after Nero began persecuting the Christians. exhorts the Saints to make their calling and election sure.  warns against false teachers.  speaks of the latter days and Christ’s second coming.</sem:object>
